Here's the xUnit equivalent:

```csharp
// xUnit has no [SetUp]/[TearDown] attributes.
// Per-test setup → constructor. Per-test teardown → IDisposable.
// One-time setup/teardown → IClassFixture<T> + a shared fixture class.

public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture() => Database.Initialize();   // [OneTimeSetUp]
    public void Dispose() => Database.Cleanup();         // [OneTimeTearDown]
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)    // [SetUp]
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose() => _context.Dispose();         // [TearDown]

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

**Key mappings:**

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` shared fixture (ctor/Dispose) |
| `[SetUp]` | Test class constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[TestFixture]` | *(removed — not needed)* |
| `[Test]` | `[Fact]` |

If you need async teardown, implement `IAsyncDisposable` instead.
